</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/attending-mandatory-training--dr-richard-dune--1682007024776.png?v=1682007029" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/attending-mandatory-training--dr-richard-dune--1682007024776.png?v=1682007029 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/attending-mandatory-training--dr-richard-dune--1682007024776_500x.png?v=1682007029 320w" width="2016" height="1344" alt="Attending mandatory training - Richard Dune, PhD -" title="Attending mandatory training - Richard Dune, PhD -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-187_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-188_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-190_">The employer should pay for mandatory training, and it should be undertaken during work time. According to ACAS, employees who started working for their employer after 6 April 2020 should have written terms in their employment contract specifying the training they must complete, including training their employer does not pay for. The employer may require employees to attend training or updates when not working, but they must give them the equivalent time off to compensate. Where employees work regular night shifts, their employer should consider this to ensure they can attend regular training updates.<br>
<br>It is important to note that any work-related training is considered "working time" under the Working Time Regulations 1998 and counts as work when calculating weekly hours.
<br>
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-191_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-193_">Refresher statutory and mandatory training






</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/refresher-statutory-and-mandatory-training--dr-richard-dune--1682011085059.png?v=1682011090" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/refresher-statutory-and-mandatory-training--dr-richard-dune--1682011085059.png?v=1682011090 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/refresher-statutory-and-mandatory-training--dr-richard-dune--1682011085059_500x.png?v=1682011090 320w" width="1766" height="1179" alt="Refresher statutory and mandatory training - Richard Dune, PhD -" title="Refresher statutory and mandatory training - Richard Dune, PhD -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-194_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-195_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-197_">Refresher courses are essential to ensure staff members are up-to-date with their mandatory training requirements. None of the professional bodies specifies how often mandatory training must be completed. Registrants remain competent and trained. 
<br><br>It is the employer's responsibility to establish its protocols and policies regarding mandatory training, and it is a contractual obligation for staff members to follow these policies.
<br>
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-198_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-200_">Common compliance training terminologies







</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/common-compliance-training-terminologies--dr-richard-dune--1682007372019.png?v=1682007375" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/common-compliance-training-terminologies--dr-richard-dune--1682007372019.png?v=1682007375 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/common-compliance-training-terminologies--dr-richard-dune--1682007372019_500x.png?v=1682007375 320w" width="1161" height="744" alt="Common compliance training terminologies - Richard Dune, PhD -" title="Common compliance training terminologies - Richard Dune, PhD -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-201_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-202_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-204_">In workplaces, there are various terms used to refer to compliance training related to both statutory and mandatory training. These terms are used by organisations to provide training to their staff.
<br><br><i>"<b>Mandatory training</b>"</i> is essential for safe and efficient service delivery and personal safety, which reduces organisational risks and complies with local policies and guidelines. It may include statutory training subjects.<br>
<br><i>"<b>Statutory training</b>"</i> is the learning that all staff must undertake to ensure an organisation meets its legal obligations.<br>
<br><i>"<b>Essential training</b>"</i> is a catch-all term used to describe both statutory and mandatory training because they are essential for the organisation.<br>
<br><i>"<b>Compulsory trainin</b>g"</i> is another catch-all term used to describe both statutory and mandatory training, making it clear that staff must complete it.<br>
<br><i>"<b>StatMand training</b>"</i> is an informal term that combines statutory and mandatory training. It is commonly used in the NHS and private healthcare settings.<br>
<br>In this article, the term <i>"<b>mandatory training</b>"</i> will be used to cover all these terms, including statutory training.
<br>
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-205_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-207_">Agreeing on common terminologies








</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/agreeing-on-common-terminologies--dr-richard-dune--1682008070738.png?v=1682008074" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/agreeing-on-common-terminologies--dr-richard-dune--1682008070738.png?v=1682008074 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/agreeing-on-common-terminologies--dr-richard-dune--1682008070738_500x.png?v=1682008074 320w" width="1613" height="974" alt="Agreeing on common terminologies - Richard Dune, PhD -" title="Agreeing on common terminologies - Richard Dune, PhD -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-208_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-209_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-211_">Training and compliance departments must agree upon common terminologies within their organisations. All training delivered within the organisation should be recorded and assessed to ensure it adheres to local and national requirements.
<br><br>To plan and execute effective training, consider the following questions:
